Module de.turnertech.tuples
Package de.turnertech.tuples

Class Tuple

java.lang.Object
de.turnertech.tuples.Tuple
All Implemented Interfaces:
Iterable<Object>, Collection<Object>
Direct Known Subclasses:
Tuple0, Tuple1, Tuple2, Tuple3
public class Tuple extends Object implements Collection<Object>

n-Tuple, the core of this package. This class models the concept of an untyped n-Tuple of any length. It provides basic functionality for creation and reading of immutable Tuples. It implements the Collection interface in a read only manner. Any calls to functions which would modify the collection will throw exceptions.

This implementation does not support null elements!

    • flatten

      public Tuple flatten()

      Removes all Tuples contained in this Tuple, and return a single "flat" Tuple. For example:

      myTuple.toString() = (4, (), 8, (((), 6)))
myTuple.flatten().toString() = (4, 8, 6)
      Returns:
      A tuple containing no sub tuples

    • size

      public int size()

      Note that the size of a Tuple is not the same as for other collections! For a Tuple, the size of the collection is the count of elements contained in this and all sub tuples. For example:

      ((), 8, ((5)), ()).size() == 2

    • iterator

      public Iterator<Object> iterator()

      Returns a "Tuple Aware" iterator which ignores empty tuples, and iterates through child Tuples. For example given the Tuple ((9, ((), 1)), 1), this Iterator will respond with:

      iter.next() == 9
iter.next() == 1
iter.next() == 1
iter.next() throws NoSuchElementException
      Specified by:
      iterator in interface Collection<Object>
      Specified by:
      iterator in interface Iterable<Object>

    • toArray

      public Object[] toArray()
      Returns the raw contents of the Tuple, such that they could be used to create another equal Tuple. For example, given the Tuple ((), 1), this function will return an Object[]{Tuple0, 1}.
